<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1951-12-11T13:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1951-12-11T13:00:00-05:00" n="70" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d70">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">320/12–1151: Telegram</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the United Kingdom</hi>
                                    (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Gifford</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                                </hi>
                            </head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#left">
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                                </seg>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1951-12-11T18:00:00+00:00">December 11, 1951—6 p.m.</date>
                                </dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>2683. Re <gloss target="#t_Embtel1">Embtel</gloss> 2669 Paris 1225
                                Dec 10. I again raised <gloss target="#t_SC1">SC</gloss> election
                                with Eden this morning. He said he had instructed Selwyn <pb facs="0142" n="120" xml:id="pg_120"/> Lloyd to hold discussions
                                with Fr and Dominions in Paris, looking toward Brit voting for
                                Greece if it appeared that enough Latin Americans and others cld be
                                won over to make it obvious that Greece wld be elected. He seemed
                                anxious to settle the matter and hoped that either on next ballot or
                                following ballot, a decision cld be reached.</p>
                            <p>He made it clear he was not definitely promising Brit wld vote for
                                Greece because they cld not make final decision until discussions
                                revealed what practical results of doing so wld be.</p>
                            <p>Sent <gloss target="#t_Dept1">Dept</gloss> 2683; rptd info Paris
                                1236.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Gifford</hi>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>